h3. Problem Definition:
For one of our customers upon doing JIRA upgrade to latest JIRA 7.3.6, one of the plugins fails with the below exception:
{code:java}
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Illegal character in path at index 1: $\{project.organization.url}
2017-05-03 08:19:34,719 http-nio-8080-exec-2 ERROR bugmaster 499x408x3 1udwv9v 10.70.1.89,10.70.200.14 /rest/plugins/1.0/installed-marketplace [c.a.p.r.c.error.jersey.ThrowableExceptionMapper] Uncaught exception thrown by REST service: Illegal character in path at index 1: $\{project.organization.url}
{code}
The JIRA UPM fails completely and customer is not able to load the page.

h3. Suggested Solution:
Customer would like to suggest to improve the logging so that UPM can give more hints on what kind of issue is causing the failure (which illegal character in this case?) and which plugin is causing the failure ?

h3. Why this is important:
This improvement will save support and our customers time while investigating UPM issues 

h3. Workaround:
By removing plugins from $JIRA_HOME/plugins/installed-plugins/  we were able to narrow down the issue to 1 of the plugins and had that removed and JIRA UPM is now working.

h5. Problem
Some JIRA tables, like the {{propertyentry}} table contains many single column indexes, but many of the of SQL queries run by JIRA actually include checks for 2 or 3 of the columns.

For example:
{{propertyentry}} has indices on:
{code}
jira728=# \d propertyentry ;
           Table "public.propertyentry"
    Column    |          Type          | Modifiers
--------------+------------------------+-----------
 id           | numeric(18,0)          | not null
 entity_name  | character varying(255) |
 entity_id    | numeric(18,0)          |
 property_key | character varying(255) |
 propertytype | numeric(9,0)           |
Indexes:
    "pk_propertyentry" PRIMARY KEY, btree (id)
    "osproperty_all" btree (entity_id)
    "osproperty_entityname" btree (entity_name)
    "osproperty_propertykey" btree (property_key)
{code}

A majority of the SQL queries run against this table include:
* ENTITY_NAME, ENTITY_ID,PROPERTY_KEY
{code}
SELECT ID, propertytype FROM propertyentry WHERE ENTITY_NAME= @P0  AND ENTITY_ID= @P1  AND PROPERTY_KEY= @P2
{code}
* entity_name,entity_id
{code:SQL|borderStyle=solid}
select O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY.property_key, O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY.propertytype from propertyentry O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY where O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY.entity_name = :1 and O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY.entity_id = :2 order by O_S_PROPERTY_ENTRY.id desc
{code}

In these cases, it is left to the database to try and determine which index should be used, which is not always efficient. It may even cause extremely slow query times.

h5. Suggestion
Add multi-column index to the table.
* Suggested index for Oracle: 
{code:sql|borderStyle=solid}
CREATE INDEX PROPERTYENTRY_ENTITY_ID_NAME ON PROPERTYENTRY (ENTITY_ID, ENTITY_NAME) TABLESPACE JIRA;
{code}
* Suggested index for PostgreSQL: 
{code:sql|borderStyle=solid}
CREATE INDEX propertyentry_idx_entity_id_entity_name
ON public.propertyentry USING btree (entity_id, entity_name COLLATE pg_catalog."default");
{code}
* Suggested index for MSSQL: 
{code:sql|borderStyle=solid}
CREATE NONCLUSTERED INDEX PROPERTYENTRY_IDX_ENTITY_ID_PROPERTY ON PROPERTYENTRY(ENTITY_ID,PROPERTY_KEY) INCLUDE(ENTITY_NAME)
{code}
** Extra reading:
*** http://stackoverflow.com/questions/179085/multiple-indexes-vs-multi-column-indexes
*** https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/relational-databases/indexes/create-indexes-with-included-columns

